<ce:para>The optimization of water consumption of first and second generation bioethanol production plants using a three-stage method is presented. The processes units that generate contaminants were defined, e.g., washing stages, cooling tower and boiler, sources of water like distillation columns or gas-liquid flash separators, sinks like fermentation processes, cooling towers, boilers, pretreatment tanks, and gasifiers. A number of treatment units to handle them such as screens, combined aerobic and anaerobic treatment, and reverse osmosis, respectively, were proposed. By energy optimization of the flowsheet together with the implementation of multi-effect columns and the design of optimal heat exchanger networks, the water to be treated in the cooling tower was reduced as well as the water loses by evaporation and drift. The use of air cooling to reduce the use of water as cooling agent had also an effect only in case of thermo-chemical processes, where the intercooling of the compression stages has a large contribution in the cooling needs. Finally, by coupling energy optimization, air cooling and the optimal design of water networks, all the ethanol production processes considered consumed &lt; 3 gal water/gal ethanol in the range of the needs for the production of gasoline. Moreover, corn ethanol was not as water intense as was reported so far and even consumed lees freshwater than any other process (1.46 gal/gal). Zero discharge was not achieved for all the production processes but small values were reported. This is an abstract of a paper presented at the 2010 AIChE Annual Meeting (Salt Lake City, UT 11/7-12/2010).</ce:para>
